TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Adoption of the M-Form Organizational Structure: A Test of Imitation Hypothesis
AU  - Mahajan, Vijay
AU  - Sharma, Subhash
AU  - Bettis, Richard A.
Y1  - 1988/10/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.34.10.1188
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.34.10.1188
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1188
EP  - 1201
VL  - 34
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The study of organizational adoption of administrative innovations has been generally guided by the imitation hypothesis. This hypothesis states that, within a relevant population of firms, an innovation is first adopted by a select few innovators who communicate and influence others to adopt it resulting in a predictable diffusion pattern. Using data on the adoption of the M-form organizational structure, this paper reexamines this hypothesis. Based on the reported results, we cannot reject the null hypothesis that organizational adoption of administrative innovations is characterized by a white-noise process. This result brings into question the appropriateness of the imitation hypothesis. Limitations and implications of the results are discussed.
AB  - The study of organizational adoption of administrative innovations has been generally guided by the imitation hypothesis. This hypothesis states that, within a relevant population of firms, an innovation is first adopted by a select few innovators who communicate and influence others to adopt it resulting in a predictable diffusion pattern. Using data on the adoption of the M-form organizational structure, this paper reexamines this hypothesis. Based on the reported results, we cannot reject the null hypothesis that organizational adoption of administrative innovations is characterized by a white-noise process. This result brings into question the appropriateness of the imitation hypothesis. Limitations and implications of the results are discussed.
